defs.docs:
This crate provides a library for parsing, compiling, and executing regular
expressions. Its syntax is similar to Perl-style regular expressions, but lacks
a few features like look around and backreferences. In exchange, all searches
execute in linear time with respect to the size of the regular expression and
search text.

defs.name: bytes
defs.docs: Match regular expressions on arbitrary bytes.

defs.name: Compiler
defs.docs:
A compiler translates a regular expression AST to a sequence of
 instructions. The sequence of instructions represents an NFA.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Create a new regular expression compiler.

defs.name: size_limit
defs.docs:
The size of the resulting program is limited by size_limit. If
 the program approximately exceeds the given size (in bytes), then
 compilation will stop and return an error.

defs.name: bytes
defs.docs:
If bytes is true, then the program is compiled as a byte based
 automaton, which incorporates UTF-8 decoding into the machine. If it's
 false, then the automaton is Unicode scalar value based, e.g., an
 engine utilizing such an automaton is responsible for UTF-8 decoding.

defs.name: only_utf8
defs.docs: When disabled, the program compiled may match arbitrary bytes.

defs.name: dfa
defs.docs:
When set, the machine returned is suitable for use in the DFA matching
 engine.

defs.name: reverse
defs.docs:
When set, the machine returned is suitable for matching text in
 reverse. In particular, all concatenations are flipped.

defs.name: compile
defs.docs: Compile a regular expression given its AST.

defs.name: Syntax

defs.name: CompiledTooBig

The compiled program exceeded the set size limit.
 The argument is the size limit imposed.

defs.name: ExecNoSync
defs.docs:
`ExecNoSync` is like `Exec`, except it embeds a reference to a cache. This
 means it is no longer Sync, but we can now avoid the overhead of
 synchronization to fetch the cache.

defs.name: ExecNoSyncStr
defs.docs: `ExecNoSyncStr` is like `ExecNoSync`, but matches on &str instead of &[u8].

Program is a sequence of instructions and various facts about thos

defs.name: insts
defs.docs: A sequence of instructions that represents an NFA.

defs.name: matches

defs.name: captures
defs.docs:
The ordered sequence of all capture groups extracted from the AST.
 Unnamed groups are `None`.

defs.name: capture_name_idx
defs.docs: Pointers to all named capture groups into `captures`.

defs.name: start
defs.docs:
A pointer to the start instruction. This can vary depending on how
 the program was compiled. For example, programs for use with the DFA
 engine have a `.*?` inserted at the beginning of unanchored regular
 expressions. The actual starting point of the program is after the
 `.*?`.

defs.name: byte_classes
defs.docs:
A set of equivalence classes for discriminating bytes in the compiled
 program.

defs.name: only_utf8
defs.docs: When true, this program can only match valid UTF-8.

defs.name: is_bytes
defs.docs:
When true, this program uses byte range instructions instead of Unicode
 range instructions.

defs.name: is_dfa
defs.docs:
When true, the program is compiled for DFA matching. For example, this
 implies `is_bytes` and also inserts a preceding `.*?` for unanchored
 regexes.

defs.name: is_reverse
defs.docs:
When true, the program matches text in reverse (for use only in the
 DFA).

defs.name: is_anchored_start
defs.docs: Whether the regex must match from the start of the input.

defs.name: is_anchored_end
defs.docs: Whether the regex must match at the end of the input.

defs.name: has_unicode_word_boundary
defs.docs: Whether this program contains a Unicode word boundary instruction.

defs.name: prefixes
defs.docs: A possibly empty machine for very quickly matching prefix literals.

defs.name: dfa_size_limit
defs.docs:
A limit on the size of the cache that the DFA is allowed to use while
 matching.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Creates an empty instruction sequence. Fields are given default
 values.

defs.name: skip
defs.docs:
If pc is an index to a no-op instruction (like Save), then return the
 next pc that is not a no-op instruction.

defs.name: leads_to_match
defs.docs:
Return true if and only if an execution engine at instruction `pc` will
 always lead to a match.

defs.name: needs_dotstar
defs.docs:
Returns true if the current configuration demands that an implicit
 `.*?` be prepended to the instruction sequence.

defs.name: uses_bytes
defs.docs:
Returns true if this program uses Byte instructions instead of
 Char/Range instructions.

defs.name: only_utf8
defs.docs: Returns true if this program exclusively matches valid UTF-8 bytes.

defs.name: approximate_size
defs.docs:
Return the approximate heap usage of this instruction sequence in
 bytes.

defs.name: Match
defs.docs: Match indicates that the program has reached a match state.

defs.name: Save
defs.docs:
Save causes the program to save the current location of the input in

defs.name: Split
defs.docs:
Split causes the program to diverge to one of two paths in the
 program, preferring goto1 in InstSplit.

defs.name: EmptyLook
defs.docs:
EmptyLook represents a zero-width assertion in a regex program. A
 zero-width assertion does not consume any of the input text.

defs.name: Char
defs.docs:
Char requires the regex program to match the character in InstChar at
 the current position in the input.

defs.name: Ranges
defs.docs:
Ranges requires the regex program to match the character at the current
 position in the input with one of the ranges specified in InstRanges.

defs.name: Bytes
defs.docs:
Bytes is like Ranges, except it expresses a single byte range. It is
 used in conjunction with Split instructions to implement multi-byte
 character classes.

defs.name: Match
defs.docs: Match represents a single match of a regex in a haystack.

defs.name: start
defs.docs: Returns the starting byte offset of the match in the haystack.

defs.name: end
defs.docs: Returns the ending byte offset of the match in the haystack.

defs.docs:
Returns the range over the starting and ending byte offsets of the

defs.name: as_bytes
defs.docs: Returns the matched text.

defs.name: Regex
defs.docs: A compiled regular expression for matching arbitrary bytes.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Compiles a regular expression. Once compiled, it can be used repeatedly
 to search, split or replace text in a string.

defs.name: is_match
defs.docs: Returns true if and only if the regex matches the string given.

defs.name: find
defs.docs:
Returns the start and end byte range of the leftmost-first match in
 `text`. If no match exists, then `None` is returned.

defs.name: find_iter
defs.docs:
Returns an iterator for each successive non-overlapping match in
 `text`, returning the start and end byte indices with respect to
 `text`.

defs.name: captures
defs.docs:
Returns the capture groups corresponding to the leftmost-first
 match in `text`. Capture group `0` always corresponds to the entire
 match. If no match is found, then `None` is returned.

defs.name: captures_iter
defs.docs:
Returns an iterator over all the non-overlapping capture groups matched
 in `text`. This is operationally the same as `find_iter`, except it
 yields information about capturing group matches.

defs.name: split
defs.docs:
Returns an iterator of substrings of `text` delimited by a match of the
 regular expression. Namely, each element of the iterator corresponds to
 text that *isn't* matched by the regular expression.

defs.name: splitn
defs.value: fn <'r, 't> (&'r self, text: &'t [u8], limit: usize) -> SplitN<'r, 't>
defs.docs:
Returns an iterator of at most `limit` substrings of `text` delimited
 by a match of the regular expression. (A `limit` of `0` will return no
 substrings.) Namely, each element of the iterator corresponds to text
 that *isn't* matched by the regular expression. The remainder of the
 string that is not split will be the last element in the iterator.

defs.name: replace
defs.value: fn <'t, R> (&self, text: &'t [u8], rep: R) -> Cow<'t, [u8]>
defs.docs:
Replaces the leftmost-first match with the replacement provided. The
 replacement can be a regular byte string (where `$N` and `$name` are
 expanded to match capture groups) or a function that takes the matches'
 `Captures` and returns the replaced byte string.

defs.name: replace_all
defs.value: fn <'t, R> (&self, text: &'t [u8], rep: R) -> Cow<'t, [u8]>
defs.docs:
Replaces all non-overlapping matches in `text` with the replacement
 provided. This is the same as calling `replacen` with `limit` set to
 `0`.

defs.name: replacen
defs.value: fn <'t, R> (&self, text: &'t [u8], limit: usize, mut rep: R) -> Cow<'t, [u8]>
defs.docs:
Replaces at most `limit` non-overlapping matches in `text` with the
 replacement provided. If `limit` is 0, then all non-overlapping matches
 are replaced.

defs.name: shortest_match

defs.name: shortest_match_at
defs.docs:

defs.name: find_at
defs.docs:

defs.name: captures_read
defs.docs:
This is like `captures`, but uses
 [`CaptureLocations`](struct.CaptureLocations.html)

 [`Captures`](struct.Captures.html) in order to amortize allocations.

defs.docs:
Returns the same as `captures_read`, but starts the search at the given
 offset and populates the capture locations given.

defs.docs: An undocumented alias for `captures_read_at`.

defs.name: get
defs.docs:
Returns the start and end positions of the Nth capture group. Returns
 `None` if `i` is not a valid capture group or if the capture group did
 not match anything. The positions returned are *always* byte indices
 with respect to the original string matched.

defs.name: len
defs.docs: Returns the total number of capturing groups.

defs.name: pos
defs.docs: An alias for the `get` method for backwards compatibility.

defs.name: Captures
defs.docs: Captures represents a group of captured byte strings for a single match.

defs.name: get
defs.docs:
Returns the match associated with the capture group at index `i`. If
 `i` does not correspond to a capture group, or if the capture group
 did not participate in the match, then `None` is returned.

defs.name: name
defs.docs:
Returns the match for the capture group named `name`. If `name` isn't a
 valid capture group or didn't match anything, then `None` is returned.

defs.name: iter
defs.docs:
An iterator that yields all capturing matches in the order in which
 they appear in the regex. If a particular capture group didn't
 participate in the match, then `None` is yielded for that capture.

defs.docs: Returns the number of captured groups.

defs.name: SubCaptureMatches

defs.name: NoExpand

 text that *isn't* matched by the regular expression.

defs.name: splitn
defs.value: fn <'r, 't> (&'r self, text: &'t str, limit: usize) -> SplitN<'r, 't>
defs.docs:
Returns an iterator of at most `limit` substrings of `text` delimited
 by a match of the regular expression. (A `limit` of `0` will return no
 substrings.) Namely, each element of the iterator corresponds to text
 that *isn't* matched by the regular expression. The remainder of the
 string that is not split will be the last element in the iterator.

defs.name: replace
defs.value: fn <'t, R> (&self, text: &'t str, rep: R) -> Cow<'t, str>
defs.docs:
Replaces the leftmost-first match with the replacement provided.
 The replacement can be a regular string (where `$N` and `$name` are
 expanded to match capture groups) or a function that takes the matches'
 `Captures` and returns the replaced string.

defs.name: replace_all
defs.value: fn <'t, R> (&self, text: &'t str, rep: R) -> Cow<'t, str>
defs.docs:
Replaces all non-overlapping matches in `text` with the replacement
 provided. This is the same as calling `replacen` with `limit` set to
 `0`.

defs.name: replacen
defs.value: fn <'t, R> (&self, text: &'t str, limit: usize, mut rep: R) -> Cow<'t, str>
defs.docs:
Replaces at most `limit` non-overlapping matches in `text` with the
 replacement provided. If `limit` is 0, then all non-overlapping matches
 are replaced.

defs.name: shortest_match
defs.docs: Returns the end location of a match in the text given.

defs.name: shortest_match_at
defs.docs:
Returns the same as shortest_match, but starts the search at the given
 offset.

defs.name: is_match_at
defs.docs:
Returns the same as is_match, but starts the search at the given
 offset.

defs.name: find_at
defs.value: fn <'t> (&self, text: &'t str, start: usize) -> Option<Match<'t>>
defs.docs:
Returns the same as find, but starts the search at the given
 offset.

defs.name: captures_read
defs.value: fn <'t> (&self, locs: &mut CaptureLocations, text: &'t str) -> Option<Match<'t>>
defs.docs:
This is like `captures`, but uses
 [`CaptureLocations`](struct.CaptureLocations.html)
 instead of
 [`Captures`](struct.Captures.html) in order to amortize allocations.

defs.name: captures_read_at
defs.value: fn <'t> (&self, locs: &mut CaptureLocations, text: &'t str, start: usize) -> Option<Match<'t>>
defs.docs:
Returns the same as captures, but starts the search at the given
 offset and populates the capture locations given.

defs.name: read_captures_at
defs.value: fn <'t> (&self, locs: &mut CaptureLocations, text: &'t str, start: usize) -> Option<Match<'t>>
defs.docs: An undocumented alias for `captures_read_at`.

defs.name: as_str
defs.docs: Returns the original string of this regex.

defs.name: capture_names
defs.docs: Returns an iterator over the capture names.

defs.name: captures_len
defs.docs: Returns the number of captures.

defs.name: capture_locations
defs.docs:
Returns an empty set of capture locations that can be reused in
 multiple calls to `captures_read` or `captures_read_at`.

defs.name: locations
defs.docs: An alias for `capture_locations` to preserve backward compatibility.

defs.name: CaptureNames
defs.docs: An iterator over the names of all possible captures.

defs.name: Split
defs.docs: Yields all substrings delimited by a regular expression match.

defs.name: SplitN
defs.docs: Yields at most `N` substrings delimited by a regular expression match.

defs.name: CaptureLocations
defs.docs:
CaptureLocations is a low level representation of the raw offsets of each
 submatch.

defs.name: Locations
defs.docs: A type alias for `CaptureLocations` for backwards compatibility.

defs.name: get
defs.docs:
Returns the start and end positions of the Nth capture group. Returns
 `None` if `i` is not a valid capture group or if the capture group did
 not match anything. The positions returned are *always* byte indices
 with respect to the original string matched.

defs.name: len
defs.docs: Returns the total number of capturing groups.

defs.name: pos
defs.docs: An alias for the `get` method for backwards compatibility.

defs.name: Captures
defs.docs: Captures represents a group of captured strings for a single match.

defs.name: get
defs.docs:
Returns the match associated with the capture group at index `i`. If
 `i` does not correspond to a capture group, or if the capture group
 did not participate in the match, then `None` is returned.

defs.name: name
defs.docs:
Returns the match for the capture group named `name`. If `name` isn't a
 valid capture group or didn't match anything, then `None` is returned.

defs.name: iter
defs.docs:
An iterator that yields all capturing matches in the order in which
 they appear in the regex. If a particular capture group didn't
 participate in the match, then `None` is yielded for that capture.

defs.name: expand
defs.docs:
Expands all instances of `$name` in `replacement` to the corresponding
 capture group `name`, and writes them to the `dst` buffer given.

defs.name: len
defs.docs: Returns the number of captured groups.

defs.name: SubCaptureMatches
defs.docs:
An iterator that yields all capturing matches in the order in which they
 appear in the regex.

defs.name: CaptureMatches
defs.docs:
An iterator that yields all non-overlapping capture groups matching a
 particular regular expression.

defs.name: Matches
defs.docs: An iterator over all non-overlapping matches for a particular string.

defs.name: Replacer
defs.docs: Replacer describes types that can be used to replace matches in a string.

defs.name: replace_append
defs.docs: Appends text to `dst` to replace the current match.

defs.name: no_expansion
defs.docs: Return a fixed unchanging replacement string.

defs.name: by_ref
defs.docs: Return a `Replacer` that borrows and wraps this `Replacer`.

defs.name: ReplacerRef
defs.docs: By-reference adaptor for a `Replacer`

defs.name: NoExpand
defs.docs: `NoExpand` indicates literal string replacement.

defs.name: SparseSet
defs.docs: A sparse set used for representing ordered NFA states.

defs.name: internal
defs.docs:
The `internal` module exists to support suspicious activity, such as
 testing different matching engines and supporting the `regex-debug` CLI
 utility.
